1 rajomN * signifies The throwing, or casting, of stones: (S, K:) this is its primary meaning: (S, TA:) you say, rajamahu, aor.
rajuma , inf. n. rajomN, (S, Msb, TA,) He threw, or cast, stones at him; or pelted him with stones: (S, TA:) or he struck him, or smote him, with rajam, meaning stones: (Msb:) and rujuwmN is syn. with rajomN, as an inf. n.: thus some explain the saying, in the Kur [lxvii. 5], wajoEalonaAhaA rujuwmFA lil$~ayaATiyni [And we have made them for casting at the devils; meaning shooting stars, which are believed to be hurled at the devils that listen by stealth, beneath the lowest heaven, to the words of the angels therein: but see other explanations below, voce rajomN]. (TA.) ― -b2- Hence, (S, TA,) The act of slaying [in any manner, but generally stoning, i. e. putting to death by stoning]. (S, K.) So in rajomu Alv~ay~ibayoni A_i*aA zanayaA [The slaying, or stoning, of the two married persons when they have committed adultery]. (TA.) ― -b3- [(assumed tropical:) The act of beating, or battering, the ground with the feet.] One says of a camel, yarojumu AlA^aroDa (assumed tropical:) [He beats, or batters, the ground], i. e., with his feet; which implies commendation: (TA:) and so one says of a horse; (K;) or yurojumu fiY AlA^aroDi. (S.) And one says also, jaA='a yarojumu, meaning (assumed tropical:) [He came beating, or battering, the ground; or] passing along with an ardent and a rapid running. (Lh, K, * TA.) [See also 8.] ― -b4- (tropical:) The act of cursing. (K, TA.) ― -b5- (assumed tropical:) The act of reviling. (K, TA.) laA^arojuman~aka, in the Kur xix. 47, means (assumed tropical:) I will assuredly revile thee: (Bd, Jel, TA: see also another explanation below, in this paragraph:) or I will assuredly cast stones at thee, (Bd, Jel,) so that thou shalt die, or shalt remove far from me. (Bd.) And you say, rajamotuhu biAlqawoli, meaning (assumed tropical:) I uttered foul, or evil, speech against him. (Msb.) [See also rajabahu.] ― -b6- (assumed tropical:) The act of driving away; expelling; putting, or placing, at a distance, away, or far away. (K.) ― -b7- (assumed tropical:) The act of cutting off from friendly, or loving communion or intercourse; forsaking; or abandoning. (K.) ― -b8- Also [as being likened to the throwing of stones, in doing which one is not sure of hitting the mark,] i. q. qa*ofN (K, TA) biAlgayobi (assumed tropical:) [The act of speaking of that which is hidden, or which has not become apparent to the speaker;
and conjecturing]; (TA;) or speaking conjecturally: (S, TA:) and (K, TA) some say (TA) i. q. gayobN [as meaning (assumed tropical:) a doubting]: (K, TA: [in the CK, AlEayobu is erroneously put for Algayobu:] and Zan~N [which means (assumed tropical:) an opining, or a conjecturing]. (K, TA.) One says, rajama biAlgayobi (assumed tropical:) He spoke of that which he did not know. (Ham p. 494.) And rajama biAlZ~an~i (Z, TA) (assumed tropical:) He spoke conjecturally: (MA:) or he conjectured, or opined. (Bd in xviii. 21.) Hence, qaAlahu rajomFA (assumed tropical:) He said it conjecturally. (Z, TA.) Hence also, (TA,) rajomFA baAlgayobi, in the Kur [xviii. 21], (S, TA,) (assumed tropical:) [Speaking conjecturally of that which is hidden, or unknown; as indicated in the S and TA: or] conjecturing in a case hidden from them. (Jel.) One says also, qaAla rajomFA biAlgayobi, i. e. (assumed tropical:) He said conjecturally, [or speaking of that which was hidden from him, or unknown by him,] without evidence, and without proof. (Msb.) And SaAra rajomFA laA yuwqafu EalaY Haqiyqapi A^amorihi (assumed tropical:) [It became a subject of conjecture, the real state of the case whereof one was not to be made to know]. (S, TA.) And laA^arojuman~aka, in the Kur [xix. 47, of which two explanations have been mentioned above], means [accord. to some] I will assuredly say of thee, [though] speaking of that which is hidden [from me], or unknown [by me], what thou dislikest, or hatest. (TA.) ― -b9- lisaAnN yurojumu [if the latter word be not a mistranscription for ↓ mirojamN, q. v.,] means A tongue that is chaste, or perspicuous, and copious, in speech. (Msb in art. trjm.) ― -b10- See also the next paragraph, in three places.

ruq~N *
Shallow, applied to water; or shallow water; (↓ maA='N raqiyqN; IDrd, K, TA;) not copious, or not abundant; (IDrd, TA;) in a sea, or great river, or in a valley; (IDrd, K, TA;) as also ↓ raq~N;
(K;) and so ↓ ruqaAriqN. (IDrd, K.) ― -b2- See also raqaAqN.
